- The derivative of this term with respect to `t` is `(y i - x i) * (derivative of nth_partial i f ((1 - t) • x + t • y) with respect to t)`.
- The derivative of `nth_partial i f ((1 - t) • x + t • y)` with respect to `t` is the sum of partial derivatives of `f` at the point, multiplied by the derivatives of the coordinates. Specifically, using the chain rule, this derivative is `∑ j, (partial f / partial (x j)) * (partial (x j) / partial t)`. The partial derivatives of `x j` with respect to `t` are `0` if `j ≠ i` and `1` if `j = i`. So, this simplifies to `(partial f / partial x i) * 1 + ...` evaluated at the point. In other words, it's the sum `∑ j, (y j - x j) * nth_partial i j f ((1 - t) • x + t • y)`. This is because `partial (x j) / partial t` is `0` if `j ≠ i` (since `x j` does not depend on `t`) and `1` if `j = i` (since `x i` is multiplied by `(1-t)`). So, when differentiating `nth_partial i f ((1-t)x + ty)`, we get `∑ j, (partial f / partial x j) * (partial (x j) / partial t) = ∑ j, (y j - x j) * nth_partial i j f ((1-t)x + ty)`. This is because `partial (x j) / partial t` is `0` if `j ≠ i` (since `x j` does not depend on `t`) and `1` if `j = i` (since `x i` is multiplied by `(1-t)` and `y i` by `t`). Therefore, the derivative of `g'(t)` is `∑ i, (y i - x i) * (∑ j, (y j - x j) * nth_partial i j f ((1 - t) • x + t • y))`.

